In mathematics, a function f from a set X to a set Y is 'surjective' (or
'onto'), or a 'surjection', if every element y in Y has a corresponding element
x in X given by f(x) = y. Multiple elements of X might be turned into the same
element of Y by applying f.

The term surjective and the related terms [[injective function|injective]] and
[[bijective function|bijective]] were introduced by Nicolas
Bourbaki,<ref>.</ref> a group of mainly French 20th-century mathematicians who
wrote a series of books presenting an exposition of modern advanced mathematics,
beginning in 1935. The French prefix [[wiktionary:sur#French|sur]] means over or
above and relates to the fact that the image of the domain of a surjective
function completely covers the function's codomain.
